content.text:
I found the root cause. This is a backend bug in the new `GET /api/user/me` endpoint — it only works for internal users, never for factory (vendor) users.

## What's happening

The frontend calls `serverAddress + '/api/user/me'` for every user on app load ([main.service.ts:418](designflow-frontend/src/app/helpers/services/main.service.ts:418)). That resolves to `https://api.alsand.designflow.app/api/core/api/user/me`. The route exists, so this isn't a routing 404 — the **controller** is returning it.

In [user.controller.js:22-27](designflow-backend/controllers/user.controller.js:22), `getProfile` does:

```js
const user = await getUserInfo(req.headers.authorization); // decoded JWT
const profile = await UserService.getProfile(user.user_id);
if (!profile) return res.status(404).json({ message: 'User not found' });
```

And [user.service.js:11](designflow-backend/services/user.service.js:11) looks the id up **in the `users` table**:

```js
sql.users.findOne({ where: { id: userId }, attributes: ['id','name','lastname','email','profile_photo'] })
```

The problem is what `user_id` means depends on who logged in:

| Login type | Token `user_id` claim | Source table |
|---|---|---|
| Internal (Azure / staff) | `users.id` | `users` ✓ |
| **Factory / vendor** | **`vendor.vendor_id`** | `vendor` ✗ |

For vendors, the JWT is signed with `user_id: data.vendor_id` ([lib.model.js:1684](designflow-backend/models/lib.model.js:1684), [std.service.js:1002](designflow-backend/services/std.service.js:1002)). So `getProfile` queries `users` with a **vendor's primary key**, finds no matching row → `null` → **404 "User not found"** → the toast you saw. (jeromechen is a vendor — that's exactly the `vendor_id: 31` row in the impersonation test fixtures.)

The endpoint was simply written assuming every token's `user_id` points at the `users` table.

## The fix

`getProfile` needs to branch on the token's `role`. For `vendor`, read from the `vendor` table by `vendor_id`. Something like:

```js
// controller passes the decoded token, not just user_id
const profile = await UserService.getProfile(user);
```
```js
UserService.getProfile = async ({ user_id, role }) => {
  if (role === 'vendor') {
    const v = await sql.vendor.findOne({
      where: { vendor_id: user_id },
      attributes: ['vendor_id', 'vendor_name', 'vendor_lastname', 'vendor_email'],
    });
    if (!v) return null;
    return {
      firstName: v.vendor_name || '',
      name: `${v.vendor_name || ''} ${v.vendor_lastname || ''}`.trim(),
      email: v.vendor_email || '',
      photoUrl: null,
    };
  }
  // existing users-table path...
};
```

One caveat: the `vendor` table has **no `profile_photo` column** ([vendor.js](designflow-backend/models/db/vendor.js)), so vendor `photoUrl` is always `null`, and the `POST /api/user/photo` endpoint has the same id-mismatch bug — it would write a `profile_photo` to a non-existent `users` row for vendors. If factory users need avatars, that needs a `vendor.profile_photo` column too.

Want me to implement the fix (with a unit test for the vendor path) on `sandbox-albert`? I'd cover `/me` for vendors now, and either fix or explicitly block `/photo` for vendors depending on whether you want factory avatars.

